content: Last 2 weeks, we have spent our energy on studying about the ways to prevent draw tactics under new opening rules.
Today we will go on with this, and I hope you will all be super active.
The more active you are, the more you learn yourself, and the happier I will be :)
Last time we spoke about Jonsson rule.
I got to leave after half this lesson,, but I will be double active when I'm here
today we will continue with it.
i don't know what jonsson rule is..
the Jonsson rule is, where first player puts the opening of 3 stones,
then white player puts 4th move, and declares how many 5th will be: 1,2,3.
when we study about the ways to escape draw position,
then we simulate that one player is a draw-maker,
and another player is the escaper
does escaper have good 4th move to play?
if escaper goes i10 and declares 3 5th,
and besides g9 and h7, he also offers h6.
so draw-maker succeeds with draw tactics
escaper goes here, and suggests 3 moves
by old rule, black only needed two 5th,
so all other 5th moves were not even analysed.
not sure black or white will have advantage
who wants to be white, say me
looks similar to 4-6 6-4,, and there its black win, right?
so maybe we change the 6th move
who wants to be white now
we had this position just before
too strong on right upper area
any other 8th possible? perhaps some active move?
who wants to try on board, say me
i fear, all passive 8 will die fast
so, we can say, here is no good draw-way for draw-maker
so, escaper must swap after 3rd move.
escaper goes 4th here, and declares 3 5th moves.
i am so messy today , always type wrong :)
escaper must take black now, otherwise drawmaker goes h6 again
so, escaper must offer 3 5th moves now.
this is the standard variant of such 5th move, i think.
if escaper doesnt get big advantage now,
then the game makes drawmaker happy
I just came up with an idea,, 5-8,, is there sure white win ther?
so, whats your opinion, is it good for black how?
i fear, black advantage is too small here,
so the draw-maker can defend easily
this 5th move may be interesting, too.
It was analysed in renjuclass maybe 4 years ago. :)
i think none of you were there at that time.
I did not know renju at that time
White has only one move here
and this variant is the only choice for both sides!
i remember that white can win after 12,14,16
haha, by the way, renjuclass has lots of "free download" material.
2002 files are already included to free downloads
this is the only white move.
and now, next black move is also the only move.
because white has win power on left,
and also the power point j9
Good luck analysing everybody,, I had to leave now,,
here white is too strong now
because black defense power is weak now
it means, white can choose between several 14th moves.
the passive 14th, to g9, is not so good
because although white can attack for a while,
and wait the attack to exhaust,
and then enjoy the black power at the bottom
And in old renjuclass, we played 15-g9.
But now, many years later, i wonder why 15-g9.
if white takes g9 now, it will transfer to position where black is happy
so white must avoid g9 now!!
seems j9 is the only chance now
so, we can do one summary now: all these 16 moves are the optimal variant for both sides.
who wants to be white now
doesnt matter which result, just try
my idea of this 17 is - black will keep win potential after defending
while, if passive 17-g9, then black is hopeless to win, even if it defends
i found this 17 about 1 hour before today's lesson
when i prepared the lesson for you
and i could not find white win.
but black had a good advantage now
black has enough power at bottom, so no need to hurry
so we proved, black keeps tempo by this 31
even can go k10 and wait
so, this variant is maybe the key of the whole opening, about the tactics of draw escaping
especially because you all worked hard today
so we got some good results
so, we can keep studying further at home
that the 5-g8 is possible and strong
